                <h3>Modules of Delight</h3>
                <p>Since musicians interact with synths through knobs, sliders and other bits of control panel, nailing the look and feel of these elements was critical. With a well-designed instrument, every touch of a control becomes  intimate, joyful and expressive.</p>
                    <p>I looked at audio hardware that was successful - UI designs that people had been using on stage for decades. But skeumorphic audio apps existed on desktop and they didn’t translate well to mobile devices, or live performance.</p>
                    <p>In my sketching and iteration, I asked:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>What does a musical instrument that can look like *anything* look like?</li>  
                        <li>What does a synthesizer look like that's powerful but also welcoming? How can a thing that's intimidating let more people in?</li>
                        <li>How can I represent a knob so a user can acquire it while they’re on a stage in the middle of a live performance?</li>
                        <li>How can I reduce cognitive load when my app isn’t sitting by itself in the user’s hand but on a rack with a dozen other pieces of complicated hardware, all competing for attention?</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>I simplified and refined the design of AnalogKit’s components until they made sense quickly, were pleasurable and welcoming to touch, and not overwhelming when put in the context of a project. We demoed an early beta at SXSW and got some great feedback. After testing, more modules followed and were added to the library of components.</p>
            </div>  
